## Risk Measure Example

One simple way to represent portfolio risk is through volatility, which can be written as:

$$
\sigma = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(r_i - \bar{r})^2}
$$

This equation shows how dispersion around the mean return can be used to measure variability and financial risk.

## Active Python Example

The following Python example demonstrates a simple return and volatility analysis. It reflects the kind of structured numerical reasoning that supports risk management and hedging work.

```{python}
#| echo: true
#| code-fold: true
#| fig-cap: "Example Python visualisation of simulated daily returns"

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

np.random.seed(42)

returns = pd.DataFrame({
    "Day": range(1, 51),
    "Daily_Return": np.random.normal(0.001, 0.02, 50)
})

volatility = returns["Daily_Return"].std()
mean_return = returns["Daily_Return"].mean()

print("Mean Daily Return:", round(mean_return, 4))
print("Volatility (Std Dev):", round(volatility, 4))

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(returns["Day"], returns["Daily_Return"])
plt.axhline(mean_return, linestyle="--")
plt.title("Simulated Daily Returns")
plt.xlabel("Day")
plt.ylabel("Return")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
This active Python example shows how return data can be interpreted through both summary statistics and visual output. It supports the wider project by demonstrating an executable form of structured financial analysis.

Reflection

This project helped me develop a stronger appreciation for how quantitative methods can support financial understanding and decision-making. I learned how important it is to interpret numbers carefully, rather than simply calculate them, because the real value of analysis comes from explaining what the results mean. The project also improved my confidence in working with more detailed and technical Excel functions. Overall, it gave me more confidence in handling structured numerical tasks and strengthened my interest in analytical work that involves both logic and interpretation.

Skills Gained

The main skills I developed through this project include Excel functions, quantitative analysis, risk interpretation, structured calculations, and financial data presentation. I also improved my ability to compare measures such as volatility, Value-at-Risk, and portfolio risk in a more organised and meaningful way. Beyond technical skills, the project strengthened my attention to detail, accuracy, and confidence in explaining numerical findings clearly. These skills are useful for finance support, business analysis, and roles involving structured data interpretation.
